Section 1: Data Description

Summary

  • The dataset our group will be working on contains information on individuals' e-commerce browsing sessions and whether their session ended with a purchase.
  • There are a total of 12330 observations made where each row/observation is one session.
  • There are a total of 18 columns where each column - excluding Revenue - falls into one of the five broader categories:
    1. Type of website visited: Administrative, Informational, ProductRelated
    2. Duration spent on website: Administrative_Duration, Informational_Duration, ProductRelated_Duration
    3. Engagement metrics: BounceRates, ExitRates, PageValues
    4. Timing & Season: SpecialDay, Month, Weekend
    5 Technical data: Operating Systems, Browser, Region, TrafficType, VisitorType
    The following table shows the type of data used to represent each of the variables and also indicates if there are any missing data for each of them.

Source and Information

Source :
Sakar, C. & Kastro, Y. (2018). Online Shoppers Purchasing Intention Dataset [Dataset]. UCI Machine Learning Repository. https://doi.org/10.24432/C5F88Q.

According to the creators, the dataset was formed so that each session/observation belonged to a different user and was obtained over the period of 1 year to avoid biases such as tendency to a specific campaign, special day, user profile, or period.

The following methods were used to collect data for each of the variables:

  • For the variables that we previously identified under the categories "Type of website visited" and "Duration spent on website", the values were derived from the URL information of the pages visited by the user and updated in real time when a user takes an action, e.g. moving from one page to another.
  • For the variables that we previously identified under "Engagement metrics", the values were derived from Google Analytics measures. Specific definitions provided for variables included:
    • BounceRate: % of session that were a single-page view.
    • ExitRate: % of pageviews for a page that were the last in a session.
    • Page value: average monetary value attributed to pages viewed before a transaction.
  • For variables under "Season& Timings" specific definitions provided were:
    • Special Day: a 01 proximity score to retail events, non-zero only within a defined window around the event, peaking on a specified date.
  • For the variables under Technical data - OperatingSystems, Browser, Region, TrafficType, VisitorType - aptured from session/analytics metadata; collection details not specified (NA).

Preselection Variables

For this project we will be dropping the following variables:

  • Page Value It uses information thats only known after a purchase, so it would cheat (leak the answer).
  • Browser no clear, consistent link to buying.
  • Operating System Similar to Browser;
  • Region Its just a numeric code with no map/explanation, so we cant interpret it reliably.
  • Traffic Type Its just a numeric code with no map/explanation, so we cant interpret it reliably.
  • Bounce Rate Overlaps with page counts/durations (single-page sessions), so its redundant.

Section 2: Scientific Question

"We want to examine if a commerce sessions purchase outcome is associated with users page-view counts and durations (Administrative/Informational/ProductRelated), and timing (Weekend or Weekday) among sessions where Region 1. In short, does browsing intensity and timing help explain which sessions convert?"

Response Variable: Revenue (Binary)

Our primary goal is inferential : to assess how browsing intensity variables are associated with the odds of purchase.

## 1) Page view counts: Administrative / Informational / ProductRelated
plot_1_dat <- new_data  %>%
  select(Administrative, Informational, ProductRelated) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    everything(),
    names_to = "PageType",
    values_to = "Count"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    PageType = factor(
      PageType,
      levels = c("Administrative", "Informational", "ProductRelated"),
      labels = c("Administrative pages", "Informational pages", "Product-related pages")
    )
  )

plot_1 <- plot_1_dat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = PageType, y = Count, fill = PageType)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.85) +
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log1p") +   # log(1 + Count) scale so small groups are visible
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Page View Counts by Page Type",
    x = "Page type",
    y = "Number of pages viewed (log(1 + count))",
    fill = "Page type"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

plot_2

Exploring the visualisation:

Why is this plot relevant:

  • These boxplots show the distributions of browsing intensity by page typeboth pages viewed and minutes spentwhich are the core inputs in our question.
  • The y-axis uses a log(1 + value) scale so that both typical sessions and extreme high-activity sessions can be seen clearly without product-related activity overwhelming the other groups.
  • Seeing the full shapes (center, spread, tails) for Administrative, Informational, and Product-related sessions helps identify typical behavior vs. extremes before adding timing or building models.

Interpretation of the results:

  • Product-related pages show the highest medians and the widest spread for both counts and durations, indicating that some users spend much more time and click far more on product pages than on the other types.

  • Administrative activity is moderate in both counts and time, while Informational pages are concentrated very close to zero, with many sessions never visiting an informational page at all.

  • The duration plots show a handful of extreme outliers (very long times) that can dominate axis scales.

What can we learn from this visualisation:

  • Product-related engagement looks most variable and potentially most informative, suggesting features like total views/duration, shares (e.g., product-related total), or interactions may matter.
  • We should also watch for collinearity between counts and their matching durations when modeling.
  • The strong skewness and outliers suggest that transformations (like log(1 + x)) or robust methods may be appropriate when modelling these variables. However, interpretations can be done more easily using raw data and counts which we will be using for the following sections.

Section 4: Method and Plan

Proposed method

  • We will use a multiple logistic regression model to relate the binary purchase outcome (purchase vs. non-purchase) to browsing intensity and timing (weekend vs weekday).

  • Predictors will include an indicator for Weekend (Weekend vs Weekday) and raw page-view counts and durations for Administrative, Informational, and Product-related pages.

  • We will use the raw data without transformation to make interpretability easier.

  • We will also check for multicollinearity using VIF.

Why this method is appropriate

  • Logistic regression is appropriate because our outcome is binary, and it directly models how predictors change the probability (or odds) of a purchase.

  • It also allows us to include several page-type and timing variables at once and interpret their effects while holding other variables constant.

Assumptions:

Assumptions (logistic regression with raw counts and durations)

  • Each session in our filtered dataset (Region 1) is treated as an independent observation.

  • The log-odds of purchase are assumed to be an approximately linear function of the browsing-intensity predictors on their raw scales (Administrative, Informational, ProductRelated counts and durations) and the weekend indicator.

  • Conditional on the predictors, the outcome follows a binomial meanvariance relationship, i.e. Var(Y | X) = p(1p), and we assume there is no substantial overdispersion relative to this model.

  • The predictors do not exhibit severe multicollinearity (e.g., counts and durations are not so highly correlated that the logistic regression coefficients cannot be reliably estimated).

Limitations:

  • Logistic regression only captures average, linear effects on the log-odds, so complex interactions or nonlinear relationships may be missed if we do not explicitly include them.

  • Strong correlations between counts and their corresponding durations could inflate standard errors and make it harder to separate their individual effects.

  • The model is observational, so even if we see strong associations, we cannot claim causal effects of browsing intensity or timing on purchases.

Section 5: Computational code and output

In[7]:
# 1. Prepare modelling dataset 
data_model_raw <- new_data  %>%
  mutate(
    # 0/1 outcome for logistic regression
    Revenue_bin = as.integer(Revenue == TRUE)
  )

# 2. Fit logistic regression with raw intensity variables
fit_logit_raw <- glm(
  Revenue_bin ~ Administrative + Informational + ProductRelated +
    Administrative_Duration + Informational_Duration + ProductRelated_Duration + Weekend,
  data   = data_model_raw,
  family = binomial
)
summary(fit_logit_raw)

The table produced shows the odds ratios (with 95% confidence intervals) for each predictor after exponentiating the logistic regression coefficients.

Interpretation of results

Page Counts:

  • Holding all other variables constant, each additional Administrative page count is associated with an expected odds of purchase multiplied by about 1.07 (95% CI: 1.0416 to 1.0907), indicating a clear positive association between Administrative engagement and conversion.
  • Holding other variables constant, the expected odds ratios for Informational and Product-related page counts are close to 1 and have p-values >0.05, suggesting little evidence that these counts are individually associated with purchase.

Durations:

  • Holding all variables constant, greater time spent on Product-related page count is associated with slightly higher expected odds of purchase (odds ratio 1.00014, 95% CI: 0.9971 to 1.0005); the change in odds for a one-unit increase in duration is very small, so this effect becomes meaningful only over large differences in time.
  • The odds ratios for Administrative duration and Informational duration have p-values >0.05, so there is no strong evidence that their individual durations are associated with purchase once the other variables are controlled for.

Weekend:

  • Holding all browsing-intensity variables constant, sessions that occur on the Weekend have expected odds of purchase multiplied by about 1.27 (95% CI: 1.0976 to 1.4654) compared to Weekday sessions (the reference level), indicating that, conditional on similar browsing intensity, weekend sessions tend to have higher odds of conversion.

Overall, the model suggests that higher Administrative engagement, longer Product-related duration, and weekend timing are associated with increased odds of purchase, helping answer the question about how browsing intensity and timing relate to conversion.
